{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772178954836,"sessionID":"ses_361eb8b90ffeYmwBV3N68Ex01B","part":{"id":"prt_c9e18d789001K1pAu2TjRce5c5","sessionID":"ses_361eb8b90ffeYmwBV3N68Ex01B","messageID":"msg_c9e18d423001OVPbp1mdn7S3jc","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_01HMyC8H9fC2pVHQEKW4rqE7","tool":"read","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/.markdownlint.json"},"error":"Error: File not found: /Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/.markdownlint.json","time":{"start":1772178954828,"end":1772178954835}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772178955238,"sessionID":"ses_361eb8b90ffeYmwBV3N68Ex01B","part":{"id":"prt_c9e18da4f001NRhDWDfM1y4h6r","sessionID":"ses_361eb8b90ffeYmwBV3N68Ex01B","messageID":"msg_c9e18d423001OVPbp1mdn7S3jc","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_01KwPKA6FjaCk9Txi5ewVvAV","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/CONVENTIONS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/CONVENTIONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Spec Conventions\n2: \n3: This document defines the rules, terminology, and templates that all documents\n4: under `spec/` must follow.\n5: \n6: ## Clean-Room Rules\n7: \n8: All spec documents are produced by reverse engineering — reading observable\n9: artifacts (source code, runtime logs, CLI output) rather than relying on\n10: undocumented design intent. The following rules enforce that constraint.\n11: \n12: 1. **Cite observable evidence.** Every behavioral claim must reference a source\n13:    location (file and line range) or a reproducible runtime observation.\n14: 2. **Never infer intent.** Describe what the code does, not why the author\n15:    chose to do it that way.\n16: 3. **Distinguish levels of confidence.** Use the confidence labels defined\n17:    below on any claim that is not directly confirmed by code.\n18: 4. **Do not copy source code verbatim** beyond short illustrative snippets\n19:    (five lines or fewer). Paraphrase logic in prose or pseudocode.\n20: 5. **Flag gaps explicitly.** Use the Open Questions section rather than\n21:    speculating in the body of the document.\n22: 6. **Version your observations.** Record the commit SHA or date range of the\n23:    source examined at the top of each document.\n24: \n25: ## Confidence Labels\n26: \n27: Place a label inline after any claim whose certainty is less than direct\n28: code confirmation. Labels use the format `[CONFIDENCE: <level>]`.\n29: \n30: | Label | Meaning |\n31: | --- | --- |\n32: | `[CONFIRMED]` | Directly verified in source code (cite file:line). |\n33: | `[INFERRED]` | Logically follows from confirmed facts but not directly observed. |\n34: | `[ASSUMED]` | Reasonable assumption; plausible but unverified. |\n35: | `[UNKNOWN]` | Not determinable from available evidence; add to Open Questions. |\n36: \n37: Omit the label only when the entire statement is `[CONFIRMED]` and the\n38: citation is present in the same sentence.\n39: \n40: ## Terminology\n41: \n42: | Term | Definition |\n43: | --- | --- |\n44: | **bead** | A discrete unit of work tracked by the `br` CLI. |\n45: | **epic** | A parent bead that groups related child beads. |\n46: | **iteration** | One pass of the Ralph loop: select, prompt, execute, evaluate. |\n47: | **phase** | A top-level command (`reverse`, `decompose`, `forward`). |\n48: | **run** | A single invocation of a phase command, identified by a `runId`. |\n49: | **session** | The OpenCode SDK conversation context for one iteration. |\n50: | **skill** | A named question set or prompt variant used during reverse. |\n51: | **template** | A Handlebars `.hbs` file that generates an agent prompt. |\n52: \n53: When introducing a term not in this table, define it in the module doc and\n54: propose adding it here via a PR comment.\n55: \n56: ## Required Section Template\n57: \n58: Every module spec must include the following sections in this order. Omit a\n59: section only if it genuinely does not apply, and note the omission with\n60: `_Not applicable for this module._`\n61: \n62: ---\n63: \n64: ```markdown\n65: # <Module Name>\n66: \n67: > One-sentence description of the module's role in the system.\n68: \n69: **Source:** `src/<filename>.ts` (examined at commit `<sha>` / `<date>`)\n70: \n71: ## Purpose\n72: \n73: Two to four sentences. What problem does this module solve and where does it\n74: sit in the overall architecture?\n75: \n76: ## Triggers\n77: \n78: What causes this module to execute? List entry points: exported functions,\n79: CLI commands, or events that invoke this module. Cite source locations.\n80: \n81: ## Inputs\n82: \n83: | Name | Type | Source | Description |\n84: |---|---|---|---|\n85: | `<name>` | `<type>` | `<caller / env / file>` | What it represents |\n86: \n87: ## Outputs\n88: \n89: | Name | Type | Destination | Description |\n90: |---|---|---|---|\n91: | `<name>` | `<type>` | `<caller / file / stdout>` | What it represents |\n92: \n93: ## Side Effects\n94: \n95: List observable effects outside the return value: file writes, environment\n96: mutations, process exits, network calls, spawned child processes.\n97: \n98: ## Failure Modes\n99: \n100: | Condition | Behavior | Recovery |\n101: |---|---|---|\n102: | `<condition>` | `<what happens>` | `<how it is handled>` |\n103: \n104: ## Dependencies\n105: \n106: | Dependency | Type | Purpose |\n107: |---|---|---|\n108: | `<name>` | internal / npm / system | Why this module uses it |\n109: \n110: ## Open Questions\n111: \n112: - List anything that could not be determined from available evidence.\n113: ```\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ## Markdown Style\n118: \n119: - Use ATX-style headings (`#`, `##`, `###`). Never use Setext underlines.\n120: - Wrap prose at 80 characters. Code blocks and tables are exempt.\n121: - Use fenced code blocks with an explicit language tag.\n122: - Prefer ordered lists for sequential steps; unordered lists for\n123:   unordered items.\n124: - Do not use bare URLs. Wrap links in Markdown link syntax.\n125: - One blank line before and after every block element (heading, list,\n126:   table, code block).\n127: - Do not use trailing spaces for line breaks. Use a blank line or HTML\n128:   `<br>` only when necessary.\n129: \n130: ## File Naming\n131: \n132: - Use lowercase kebab-case: `run-state.md`, `output-parser.md`.\n133: - Match the source filename where possible (drop the `.ts` extension).\n134: - The two meta-documents (`README.md`, `CONVENTIONS.md`) are the only\n135:   permitted uppercase filenames in `spec/`.\n\n(End of file - total 135 lines)\n</content>","title":"spec/CONVENTIONS.md","metadata":{"preview":"# Spec Conventions\n\nThis document defines the rules, terminology, and templates that all documents\nunder `spec/` must follow.\n\n## Clean-Room Rules\n\nAll spec documents are produced by reverse engineering — reading observable\nartifacts (source code, runtime logs, CLI output) rather than relying on\nundocumented design intent. The following rules enforce that constraint.\n\n1. **Cite observable evidence.** Every behavioral claim must reference a source\n   location (file and line range) or a reproducible runtime observation.\n2. **Never infer intent.** Describe what the code does, not why the author\n   chose to do it that way.\n3. **Distinguish levels of confidence.** Use the confidence labels defined\n   below on any claim that is not directly confirmed by code.\n4. **Do not copy source code verbatim** beyond short illustrative snippets\n   (five lines or fewer). Paraphrase logic in prose or pseudocode.\n5. **Flag gaps explicitly.** Use the Open Questions section rather than","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772178955231,"end":1772178955238}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772178955629,"sessionID":"ses_361eb8b90ffeYmwBV3N68Ex01B","part":{"id":"prt_c9e18dbe1001X71r2rhLiFMBT8","sessionID":"ses_361eb8b90ffeYmwBV3N68Ex01B","messageID":"msg_c9e18d423001OVPbp1mdn7S3jc","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_019YFUmd4R8fuM2Z4wnGgmxf","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/README.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Spec Directory\n2: \n3: This directory contains reverse-engineered specifications for the super-ralph\n4: agent framework. All documents are produced by reading observable behavior,\n5: source code, and runtime artifacts — not from internal design documents or\n6: author interviews.\n7: \n8: ## Purpose\n9: \n10: The `spec/` tree provides a clean-room description of how super-ralph works so\n11: that:\n12: \n13: - Contributors can understand module contracts without reading all source code.\n14: - The forward phase can use these docs as authoritative context when\n15:   implementing beads.\n16: - Reviewers have a stable reference for verifying that behavior matches intent.\n17: \n18: ## Scope\n19: \n20: Specifications cover the following layers:\n21: \n22: - **Engine** — The core Ralph loop (select, prompt, execute, evaluate).\n23: - **Phases** — Reverse, decompose, and forward phase orchestration.\n24: - **Subsystems** — Configuration loading, bead integration, OpenCode SDK\n25:   adapter, template resolution, run-state persistence, and output parsing.\n26: - **CLI** — Command-line interface surface and option handling.\n27: \n28: Out of scope: internal OpenCode SDK implementation, beads-rust internals, and\n29: third-party tooling not imported by this project.\n30: \n31: ## Navigation\n32: \n33: Read documents in this order for a top-down understanding:\n34: \n35: 1. [CONVENTIONS.md](CONVENTIONS.md) — Writing rules, clean-room constraints,\n36:    confidence 